metadata.name: Intangible #179
metadata.description:
Let me take you places. Those are not in your town, not even on your planet. They’re placed somewhere between reality and subconsciousness.
Enormous, peculiar structures emerge upon you, refusing to be ignored. They are your unfulfilled cravings or ever-lurking demons. They were always there, under your skin, intangible, now they’ve materialized.
You may not like them, they may seem too vast, too scary to tame. But ultimately, you have to face them, unless you enjoy living in their shadow. 

___
Inspirations

I’ve never truly realized that, but ever since I remember, the sight of gigantic objects or creatures evoked strong emotions within me.
It probably started with playing Shadow of Colossus (a video game) as a kid and seeing The Cathedral (short movie by Tomasz Bagiński). Years later, reading Solaris (by Stanisław Lem) aroused the same feeling (among others) of being mesmerized by the vastness. More recently, movies like Denis Villeneuve’s Arrival (which also nudged my attraction to mystery) and Dune - have charmed me.

Earlier this year I have stumbled across Dawid Planeta (artist and yoga teacher) and began contemplating his visions of mini people in the jungle inhabited by giant animals. These works in particular, plus Hollow - generative series by Jacek Markusiewicz - were probably my final inspirations to make Intangible look the way it does.

Settling semi-random generative structures in some kind of reality, gave them a meaning - they may symbolize things much bigger than you - the ones you try to escape from or those you’ve been longing to experience for years. I have mine, don’t you?

___
Controls in live mode


Keyboard
[ space ] - toggle light animation
[ S ] - save image with current size (default is 120% of browser window’s height; you may change browser’s scale or check URL size param)
[ F ] - fullscreen 
[ up / down ] - light intensity
[ left / right ] - base light position
[ 1..5 ] - aspect ratio: 10:16 („zero” ratio), 1:1.4142 (vertical A4), 1:1, 1.4142 (horizontal A4), 16:10
[ B ] - toggle border
[ Z ] - toggle canvas „raw” mode - no shadow / margin (auto applied in fullscreen mode)
[ N ] - toggle „that thing you may not want on print”


URL params
You may add any number of parameters to the URL to start it with particular settings. 
[ animate ] (1/0) - toggle light animation
[ size] (number) - number of px for longer edge, i.e. 4000
[ ratio ] (number or ratio with format: 10/16, 10:16, 10_16) - aspect ratio
[ light ] (number 40..120, some palettes have slightly different limits for good results) - light intensity
[ lightShift] (number -100..100) - base light position
[ border ] (1/0) - toggle border
[ hddcy ] (0/1)

Example: [ &size=4000&border=1&light=100&animate=1 ] 


Mobile
[hold 2 fingers for 2s] - save
[double tap] - fullscreen


___
Note:
I encourage you to do some light adjustments before you save an image for print. I’m pretty sure you can do better than fxrand().


___
Special thanks to my brother Krzycho, for lots of advices / heathy criticism and to Olga, for never-ending excitement and „dorady”.

___
Developed in Javascript, using p5.js (2D Canvas) and chroma.js.

metadata.name: Meet Arty #129
metadata.description:
Future royalties are shared 50% with the original minters!

Who is Arty?

Arty is the name given to this symbol by the friendly folks of Newberry, South Carolina. The symbol itself can be seen carved into the architectural moulding of the Old Newberry Hotel (est. 1878). No one knows why, when or by whom the symbol was created but many of the artists of Newberry Made have adopted it as their maker’s mark. Learn more about us at www.NewberryMade.com. 

#NewberryIsAnArtTown

Why is there a Red Dot in the bottom corner?

The red dot is my signature for an ongoing series of generative art on fxhash (a shout-out to my first project). I will continue to utilize red dots as a design element in future work.

About the token

- The canvas is square and responsive based on your viewport
- Press “s” to save (image file type is SVG)
- Owners will be given priority access to future reserve lists
- Coded using p5js & SVGCanvas v2.0.3


About the Artist

Robert Matheson is a community engaged artist from Newberry, South Carolina. His work is focused on improving the health and well-being of others through the arts. In 2019 Robert established Newberry Made, a local artist & maker registry that has grown to over 190 members.

Robert's most recent creation is the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC. A creative space focused on providing NFT art education, collaboration and exhibition to help artists and the broader community benefit from emerging digital economies. Learn more at www.RobertMatheson.com and www.NonFungibleTokenMuseum.org

Personal Use NFT License

The owner of this NFT is granted personal use rights only. For commercial use or to create derivative works, contact the artist. Copyright 2022.

metadata.name: The Fractured Fields #11
metadata.description:
You are out on the Fractured Fields hunting for gems.

Gems out here get infused with "windshine" from the eternal winds always blowing across the fields.

Infused gems can be used for "glowcasting" ~ a magical ability to transmute materials ~ and are thus extremely valuable.

The 10 Kingdoms of Mara Pakaru that surround the fractured fields compete on collecting the largest amount of gems.

Each field you come across has a 40% chance of holding a gem deposit. For each field with a gem deposit there is a 40% chance of finding a gem. Gems increase in rarity depending on how many sides they have.

The most rare of the gems are the gem-hearts. Only 1/100 gems are gem-hearts. Gem-hearts are said to contain parts of the heart of the field-god himself, and are infused with a astonishing amount for windshine.

Which Kingdom will you join?
How many gems will you collect?
And who will strike it big and dig up a gem-heart?

Ctrl+S to save high-res png.

Inspiration
--
* The Stormlight Archives by Brandon Sanderson
* RectangleWorld blog by Dan Gries
* Canvas Sketch library by Matt DesLauriers

Libraries (from npm)
--
* canvas-sketch
* density-clustering
* convex-hull
* seed-random

metadata.description:
This <Unfavorable tanshiro 100> will be the final release of this series. 

Unfavorable Tanshiro is a p5.js generative character made by @tanshiro1986.
Everyday I draw a new factor, and post a unique Tanshiro on twitter. 

Today is the 100th day since Tanshiro's birth.
Unfavorable Tanshiro #1~#99 were released on Opensea as daily record, and this memorable #100 will be concluded, improved, and released on fx(hash).

There are 1000 unique Tashiro coming from 2,400,000 different combinations.
Some special factors are the collab with JT's artwork. 

My Twitter: https://twitter.com/tanshiro1986
